text: I'm so glad they've made this movie, but ad campaign wise? I feel like this trailer is going to compel a lot of already pro-life Christians to flock to the theaters, but no one who needs their minds changed. Anyone pro-abortion would see this trailer and roll their eyes and scoff at all the Christianese and pro-life buzz phrases. Everything from the declaration that it's from the same makers as "God's Not Dead," to the dialogue they included about being a baby from conception and the prayer committing the babies' souls to God is going to drive pro-abortion people away from the theaters, not invite them in to have their perspectives changed. And don't get me wrong, that dialogue belongs in the movie. Just maybe not the trailer, if they actually want to reach the lost. For the trailer, they should have focused more on the angle of finding out what really happens in these facilities, and emphasized how this is a true story. The vast majority of pro-abortion people are not going to want to pay to watch this movie based on this trailer, especially when all the spoilers and plot points are given away already. There's no mystery left here. No intrigue. No "I wonder what happens in this movie?" Even the procedure that changed Abby's mind is framed up nice and special in the trailer so that everyone knows THAT'S the moment, and everyone at the movies will know what's coming and it won't be as shocking and jarring as it should be. I believe this movie could change lives, and save lives, but only if the ad campaign can get pro-abortion people in the door.

text: As a Catholic Pro-Life Woman, I wish I felt more positive. Some people who read this comment may assume that because I don't wholeheartedly support this film, that I support abortion, or disregard Abby Johnson as bigoted and her story as one-sided.Â  I do not.Â  I am an advocate for the safety, health and dignity of all unborn children and the mothers that carry them. Abortion is always a tragedy and those involved and targeted deserve much better. That being said, I am concerned about this film because I believe that the story, struggle, recovery and wisdom of this brave woman will not be given at least an equal placing amongst the message it's trying to send.  As proud as I am of Abby Johnson for being brave enough to hand over her story to the cast and crew, who in turn are brave enough to bring it to life, especially within a pro-abortion world like this, I am not convinced that this film will accomplish its mission. I was looking forward to this film until I saw a statement, from Abby Johnson herself, that the reason for this film's existence was for conversion. In an interview with the directors of the film, they admitted that this film was here to explain the harms of abortion.  As a college Creative Writing student, I can wholeheartedly say, from experience and spectating, that message-driven or purpose-driven stories will always fail to connect with whoever views them, or will only connect with those who understand and not with those willing to give it a chance. This is because storytelling and most forms of art are revolved and are remembered by the journeys, feelings, revelations and respectability of the characters within them. Characters who react to their hardships in the *world.* Storytelling is a way to bond over experience, emotion, desire and acknowledgement of hardships. It is one of the last platforms of unification amongst humans today. I have gotten to know people during my lifetime and heard stories from others that have chosen abortion, even if they know what abortion does, because they did not have the needs to continue the pregnancy, the people to support them, or the means to provide for themselves and stay healthy during the pregnancy.   If a storytelling platform is used for a piece that's main mission is to "convert" or to explain to them why they should believe something, by definition, it's propaganda. Audience members and citizens do not go to films or consume any type of entertainment for these reasons. I once heard a saying, "God does not wish that anybody would perish, but we know that He doesn't force people to turn to him." If we give people material that is about why they should change their minds, we are communicating that we don't accept them as they are, that we don't trust them to understand our side, and that our side is more important. Instead of being character-oriented, it's self-serving. This type of attitude and treatment, especially towards citizens who don't identify as pro-life, will always divide more than unify. And Abby Johnson's story and struggles are wholly undeserving of such injustice. It can be a fantastic accomplishment if it brought awareness to all struggles surrounding the issue and was dedicated to the perseverance, self-respect, emotions and recovery of the human beings involved, but the purpose of "conversion" does not convince me that this will be the case.  I hope that I am wrong about my prediction that this film will not succeed. I hope that Abby Johnson, and the filmmakers, and their followers will continue to fight for the rights of unborn children, and the care taking and empowerment of their often vulnerable, struggling mothers. I hope that this film does inspire some pro-lifers to behave less hostilely towards people who believe differently from them. And yes, I know that because of this pro-abortion world, many people will unfairly judge this film, some without even seeing it. But although this admittedly does look more human-oriented and less black-and-white than most faith and Christian-related films today, I am scared of the outcome because of the statement of purpose from those responsible for it. If we truly want to invite people into our world, we need to make stories about people. Faith-related films such as *The Prince of Egypt* and *Silence* have non-religious fans because they accomplish that. Being a storyteller makes me more human because it makes me more aware and open to human hardships. It doesn't have to have a solution, sometimes just recognition is enough. We will be far better off with trusting our audience's judgements and opinions than trying to format them under our worldview, however noble they might be.
author: G.C. Bolling

text: This is a great movie and I think it is awesome that it has been made. I believe it has the potential to save thousands of innocent babies lives in their mother's wombs....  But I think we can all do a little bit more to help stop the evil of abortion, because whether we like it or not, knowingly or not, we are contributing to it and sharing in it, in our everyday lives through the purchases and decisions we make.   For example Nike, Coca-Cola, Pepsi, Johnson and Johnson, McDonalds, KFC, Pizza Hut, Amazon, Starbucks, New Balance, Expedia, Wotif, Amex, Ford.... just to name a few, these are all directly or through other parties donating money, that is your money, to Planned Parenthood and/or other abortion providers.... all you have to do is go to 2ndvote.com and at the top of the screen, there is a search bar and just type in the company you wish to look up, and it will list what this company is doing with your money.... and what they are supporting financially and otherwise.  There are 1.2 billion Catholics in this world and there are in excess of 2 billion Christian's in this world and there are well over a billion Muslims in this world who also do not believe in abortion.... and there are many other people who are non religious but who are pro-life because they know how evil it is to tear up a little baby in its mother's womb and/or to take a human life no matter how small or formed.  Do you know the difference we could all make if even half of us stopped making purchases from these companies. When enough of us hurt their bottom line and their profit, they will stop their practices. On top of that we share in the guilt of what they are doing if we knowingly continue to buy from them, unless of course it is a medicine or something you can't absolutely avoid, or something that is free.  Apart from all essential medicines and things like that, I myself have stopped using these companies, and yes, it requires some sacrifice, and yes it requires us to be white Martyrs of the 21st Century, but can anybody tell me that a pair of shoes or a burger or a of soft drink, or accommodation on a holiday you can get somewhere else, or an item on sale at Amazon, is worth Killing babies to have. In many circumstances there are alternatives anyway but even if there are not, I will not do this, even sometimes it will cost a little more. and financially I am not very well off. But I want to put God first. I want to put Jesus first. I want to put these babies and their mother's first.  It is great to go out and watch this movie and to go the prayer vigils, like 40 days for life, etc, and to pray for an end to all of this and for the souls of these babies and their parents, but there is more we can do.... so much more.... but yes, it will hurt.  But think of the Sacrifice Jesus went through on the Cross for us. And think of the sacrifice these little babies are going through when they are TORN APART and mutilated, and being robbed of their lives laid out ahead of them.... And think of the sufferings of their mothers (and fathers too) either or physically (for the mothers) and mentally and spiritually after she [they] realises the truth of what was done.  Please, participate in this, spread this with everyone all over social media and in your circles, and let us do more practically to end abortion, and even more so, as to not participate in it with our money, the money we spend and what we choose to spend it on.  God bless you all good people, and keep up the fight :-) :-) And remember brothers and sisters, love is not just a mere emotion or feeling. Love is an act of the will. And thus, sometimes that act hurts Again, think of the Passion and the Cross of Jesus. True Love can hurt.

text: Wellâ€¦ what planned parenthood in my country is actually a national healthcare program where birth control is an option for couples who wants to choose the best contraception for them, also a campaign to limit 2 children per family to control the population number. (Because most families who doesn't have access to birth control end up having a lot of children yet unable to provide for all of them, which results in poverty). Elective abortion without any underlying medical condition is considered illegal, in which the anyone willingly involved in the abortion is punishable by law. To be honest, as a doctor myself, I don't understand how in people's comments doctors refused to give patients access to birth control (especially the permanent ones such as vasectomy or tubectomy) for the reason that "you might change your mind later"? Like, there's this thing called informed consent, which is a signed statement that the patient has given their consent for a certain procedure to be done to them, & that the consent was given *after* they were being informed about that particular procedure (the objective, what is done, the risk & benefits, etc). This absolves the physician from risk of lawsuit in case the patient does change their mind. This is definitely should be an option, instead of legalizing elective abortion. Planned parenthood should comprise preventing unwanted pregnancy, planning how many children you want to have, how many years apart between siblings, what should be done when you want to stop having more children & a support system how to survive an unplanned pregnancy without any harm not only to both the mother & the baby, but also the family.

text: Thought experiment, if abortion continues to be legal, by all means do it, but I would like it to be illegal to declare the baby not alive in the moment of conception, and I would like pro abortion define abortion as ending the baby's LIFE, what ever the mother reason is, valid or not valid. Remove all pursuit and campaign of answering the question whether the baby is a living being or not, but continue to legalize abortion. That way, no dishonor to the baby's life, no dishonor to the mother. Fair right? I do wonder what will happen hypothetically if that is to be implemented in real life.  Personally, I think in some situations and countries, it is a necessary evil like war. Murder is evil. A soldier defending a country and killing their enemies is ending a life, its still under the umbrella of evil perhaps a lesser one than murdering someone out of vengeance or hate, but it was necessary to win the war. Legalizing abortion is not condoning whats right, but as a dam of damage control. Because if its not legal, women will try to get it in more dangerous ways. Does it make it right? Not for me. Is it glorious? No. Worthy of praise? No. Practical and necessary? Yes. I don't believe all things legal equate to moral. So its not so much the act of abortion that enrages me, its the denying the baby is a living thing. My point is, some necessary things require dirtying your hands, and trying to deny the dirt and erasing it is disingenuous. So...abort the baby, but please acknowledge its life.  By the way, I am Christian and I do believe because this world is broken by sin. The analogy is like this. The world is threatened to be swallowed by a giant wave (sin/death/evil). Legalizing abortion is the dam that keeps the damage of the wave at bay (because without Christ the next best guardian is the law), but the wave is still there. A woman is raped, the rapist sins against her. The woman is pregnant, chooses to abort the baby, that is also sin because it ends life, but maybe her intentions are not evil, but both rapist, woman and baby are affected by sin. But the believer's hope is that wave...no longer have power over them, which is why ideally, believers given the choice, would not choose abortion, because they have a different law in their heart. Woman gets raped, rapist sins against her. Woman relies on the power of Jesus to not abort the child, cycle of sin is broken.  Well, in an ideal world, no one aborts the baby, because means to take care of the baby, to raise them to healthy happy adults are always in reach. But the world is far from ideal, some laws are necessary, because the means are not always in reach. But for those whose hope is in Christ, I pray they would not make that choice, I pray they put their faith that God provides and that God is the shepherd of their life.

This move needs to be seen (regardless if they take a few liberties or not) because Planned Parenthood has been trying to cover up their wickedness for much too long.   (On a side note, the whole foundation of Planned Parenthood was started by Margaret Sanger, a woman who promoted Eugenics.  This is the practice of selective breeding-basically wiping out children you find undesirable.  Sanger was against any children that she deemed "feeble-minded," as well as any children of color.  This practice was really promoted by Francis Galton, Charles Darwin's cousin, who took Darwin's evolutionary writings to the next level; if there was survival of the fittest, then it was only "right" to breed out those that weren't "fit."  This is the reason most abortion clinics are in minority and low-income areas, to follow Sanger's original plan.  According to statistics, there have been more African-American deaths by abortion than from urban crime, diseases, and accidents in the last three decades.  Ungodly ideas have consequences.  When you start out thinking that man isn't made in God's image and is just a random chance product of evolution, then you naturally have no problem killing those that you find undesirable.  Hence, the abortion industry.)

text: I am deeply grateful for this movie.  I had the privilege of seeing Unplanned at a screening in December.  Apart from its timely message, this is actually kind of a beautiful movie in its own right.  I don't generally cry at movies, but the final scene of this one brought me, as a parent, (pretty close) to tears - bittersweet tears.  The movie does not shy away from some of the less savory demonstrations that attach to the pro-life cause; it is credible.  But it pays particular attention to the quiet, patient, untiring, and ultimately successful vigil sustained by 40 Days For Life outside Abby Johnson's Planned Parenthood clinic.  Unlike some pro-life presentations, this film carefully, perhaps reverently avoids much in the way of graphic depiction.  Its most shocking scene is extraordinarily brief -- and a real gut punch.  But this and its few other graphic scenes are not gratuitous; each serves to illustrate carefully an important point about the reality of Planned Parenthood's gruesome practices.  Unplanned surely sharpened my outrage at the duplicity, the horror of Planned Parenthood's tactics and strategies.  But in the end it points towards healing, hope, love.  I urge all who wish to educate themselves further about the power of choice â€“ the choice Abby Johnson made and has courageously pursued â€“ to go see this movie in a theater near or even far from you, and bring as many friends and compatriots as you can.

text: The battle against this atrocity begins with identifying it correctly. By calling it "abortion," we've already acquiesced to the opposition's terminology. Look up "abortion" and "miscarriage" in any dictionary. A miscarriage is an abortion. What doctors (and parents) do to infants in the womb is infanticide. Had Roe v. Wade been waged over infanticide rather than abortion, it would have never made it to the court room. In fact, by employing the word "abortion," Roe v. Wade was won before it ever got to court.  The Greek word "brephos" employed in the New Testament for infants already born is the same word used for infants in the womb  (Luke 2:12 and Luke 1:41), without specifying the precise moment they became a "brephos." Therefore, our only option is to then accept that they became such at conception. Thus, intentionally killing a brephos at any point is "brephocide" or, more properly, infanticide.  The same is true regarding the Old Testament Hebrew word translated "child."  The point being, we Christians need to stop using the non-Christians' watered-down, politically correct terms such as "abortion" and "gay." It's infanticide and sodomy. There is no power in the former terms against evil and our first mistake is in acquiescing to the ungodly's terminology.  Listen to Part 1 of "Word Wars & Captive Thoughts" at http://www.missiontoisrael.org/tapelist.php#T849

text: Even before I was an atheist (i'm mentioning this because it a pureflix film, so its got to have some christian shit in it), i never fully agreed with being against pro-life. I understand the reasoning behind the Pro-life agruement (hell its been shoved down my throat since the conversation got started), but I don't agree and I think that this movie will make it hard for children in a christian household fell like they don't have a choice. You can argue that the 'baby' or 'fetus' has not choice, but think of it this way:   I get pregnant and know I am not in a place in my life to have a child (the reason doesn't matter. it is mine and that's what matters). I look into adoption and see that the United States foster system already has thousands of children who are not adopted and more than likely not be. It is a slim chance that a few month old will be adopted and after four years, the chance goes down even more. What do I do?  I would never have a late term abortion--unless it was a true medical emergency. Call me selfish. I am. I am twenty years old and I don't know if I want to have natural children anyway. Don't take away my option to make another child's life good when I'm ready. (Also, for those of you who see this and say I shouldn't have sex, okay. at this point in my life I have not had sex yet. That argument doesn't work for me at the moment. Also, you can be abstinent and still become pregnant. I know that it is rare, but there is still a chance.) Also, Planned Parenthood does so much more than just abortions. It give free birth control to women who couldn't otherwise afford it. It does screenings and so much more. If movies like this are done, we need to look at everything. Lastly, Pureflix, why is this rated R? If you want a message to get out to people, don't limit your audience. AND is there any graphic material that would qualify it as being rated R, or is it just the topic of the movie?"

text: I know this is a long comment, but for those of you that will listen. I hope that this may provide you clarity as to the views of pro choice women and people. =Edited for easier reading=  Planned Parenthood is an organization that, yes, provides abortion procedures to those the need or want it, but they also provide low cost if not free birth control, condoms, and sex education among other things like sti/std medication and annual exams. Honestly I'm not a sexually active person, but I'm grateful of the services they provide for their community.   Having a baby could seriously interfere with their education, work, or finances if they could not afford a baby at the time. If they already have kids it could make it harder to care for the children they already have. I know that for many young people in high school and college, having a baby recklessly could ruin their chances at pursuing their education, if not completing a high school education. It's a similar complication for people that work even a nice salary job, not planning when you have a child meticulously could ruin your life. For some women they want a child and they have everything going and disaster strikes.   Late term abortions are not some random decision like, 'oh i wanted this baby, but now i don't, oh well, let's pop it out and toss it in the can ðŸ˜' Late term abortions typically have to happen, because either the child is already dead in the womb, the child is killing the mother, or the child has congenital defect that will kill the child shortly after birth. It is a genuine life or death decision. To know that as much as 61% of the women that get abortions are already mothers they have their children, this one was not planned for or is unable to be had, but in the future they may want anouther. Think of it like this, a woman has a pregnancy that she in unable to handle for one reason or anouther it will kill her, the child could live and not have a mother and become a ward of the state, or she gets the abortion and lives to see her family again, to later have a successful pregnancy down the road.   I know of a young woman that was a mother in a very Christian community that had been (if i remember the details correctly she had 2 kids already and wanted a 3rd with her husband) with child and she had gone to her doctor and he told her that it was not viable for her to go to term and it would cost her life, well she was thinking of getting an abortion and trying again. However because the community was so closeknit they all found out and they shamed her into not getting the abortion and going to term. She ended up dying with the child. They called her brave and that she was gone too soon. She left two children and a husband, she left her entire family because of the shame people put on this woman for wanting to protect her own life.  I wish I could take this woman's account at face value, and taking it as such, the doctor that botched her abortion this badly should have been sued for medical malpractice and emotional labours they caused this woman if this were what happened. I've always been someone that wants to let people choose thier own lives, wanna be gay? Do it. Wanna be straight? Do it. Wanna end up in jail? I recommend against it, but sure do it. You can't control what other people do. But when you say that people need to die because you don't like their life choices they you need to take a look at yourself.

I think it's extremely selfish for other people to tell someone to keep a baby they don't want. That's not your fetus, you're not carrying it, and you are not the one who has to experience the after effects of pregnancy.    If you actually considered the child or the mother you wouldn't be forcing the mother to carry the child to term. It's immoral. The mother is the most important part of the process yet you clearly don't care about her at all. Abolishing abortion will just lead to black market abortion, possible suicide, possible depression, but will definitely lead to a stressful pregnancy and more likely than not lots of complications.    I've actually known someone who was an unwanted child and they said they'd rather have been aborted because she was neglected and abused. It doesn't matter what your intentions are if it ends up being bad anyway. You don't know what will become of that child. I wish you guys would think of stuff from reasonable and logistic point of view rather than an emotional one. I'm definitely pro-choice.

text: February 1976 while home alone, no car, no phone to call for help, I miscarried my 4 month term baby girl. I put her in a bowl and put her in the refrigerator and walked half a mile to find a phone so I could call for help.  I was 19 years old.  We had just moved out into the country and didn't have phone service yet.  It was hell and after all these years it still hurts.  I'm blessed to have 3 grown children and 4 wonderful grand-kids,  but my first baby girl will always be in my heart.  I still morn her on her birthday every year.  There is no WAY IN HELL you can tell me that a baby in the womb is not a living being.  Abortion is Satan's way of killing off what he hates the most, God's creation of mankind. Really, that's the examples you chose? OF COURSE it's horrible when a CHILD dies, but not a goddamn clump of cells. A Heartbeat is not a Brain, so it's STILL not a child even if it has a heartbeat.  Abortions are expensive, and the percentage of people who do them just because they can are ridiculously low, like 0.001% low. Women who get them do it because either their birth control failed (another thing you psycho pro-birthers keep trying to make harder to get, because god-forbid a woman wants to have sex with her partner and NOT get pregnant, but that's just blasphemy to you nutjobs, isn't it?), they are not mentally/physically/financially stable enough to have a child, or they have done the tests available to check for certain conditions, such as Downs, and chosen to terminate so the child won't have such a rough quality of life, which would also be a drain in many ways on their parents. (Obviously I have nothing against any person who has any type of disability, but life is rough enough without them, and I feel bad for them knowing that the majority of them will never live a full life due to having to be dependent on someone forever, not to mention the parents who have to care for them for the rest of their lives as well) Then of course there's your cases of rape, and if any of you thinks a woman, or a young girl should be forced to carry and deliver her rapists child, and think you're going to heaven? Like the 11-year-old girl who couldn't get an abortion because of bullshit in her country, just look up '11 year old gives birth". Do you think this is okay? Do you really really think that getting an abortion would've been WORSE than an actual living feeling thinking CHILD carrying and birthing her rapists child?   Abortion should be easily accessed for those who need it, and honestly for those who want it, because we women should not be punished for having sex. Men are seen as great heroes to other men when they fuck multiple women, but a woman who has more than one partner is seen as a whore or a slut. It's disgusting.  There are billions of human beings on this planet; We are currently in no danger of becoming extinct (unless we kill each other via war, but that's another topic) We do not need to worry about consistently procreating, whether or not that is our basic function, we have supposedly grown and evolved past that point.  You will never change my mind, I will always be Pro-Choice. I support your choice not to get an abortion, to keep your child, to give your child up for adoption, whatever, but I also support HER choice to abort her pregnancy, to not give up her life and dreams just to kneel to society's idea of what a woman should be doing.  I don't want kids. I don't want to bring a kid into this world that is steadily going to hell-in-a-handbasket, I don't want to pass on my medical/mental problems, and I don't want to give up my life, my time and my distant dreams to raise a kid that I would forever hold resentment for.  No child should be born to someone who would resent them, and the majority of people who get abortions know that they would feel that way. It's not wrong to not want kids, to not like kids, and to know yourself enough to know that having kids will not be good for you. I'm okay with people thinking that I'm selfish for not wanting kids, because I don't give a damn what you think. It's MY life, not yours. You don't get to tell me what to do with it.   By the way: What the FUCK happened to separation of Church and State? Because it seems to me that Religion is having way too big of a hand in lawmaking right now, and needs to fuck right off. You have your freedom of religion, but when your Religion steps on the freedom of others, that's not right. Not everyone subscribes to your Sky Daddy, and this is not a Christian Nation no matter what you loonatics would like to believe. You have your right to practice whatever religion you want, but I have the right to not practice a religion at all, which I don't.   Keep Religion out of Politics.  I am Pro-Choice.

text: I don't see the abortion question through the prism of religion. I believe in God to be sure, but organized religion..not so much. I certainly have a lot of respect and admiration for people who do have that faith. Our country was built on these very sacred principles. But my argument is more or less secular in nature. When I was younger my opinion was "hey, if you don't like abortions then don't have one." But combat service as an Army medic and a career with the fire department has afforded me the opportunity to help in the delivery of A LOT of babies. It's always an awe inspiring thing to be a part of.  What has moved me into the pro-life guy I am today is not just the experiences but also the behavior of those who advocate abortion. I find them to be often very callous and uncomfortably cavalier in their attitude towards ending a human life. I honestly think some of these people, like the cartoonish super villain Kermit Gosnell, actually ENJOY performing abortions. But at the end of the day, all you have to do is follow the money. The protection of ill gained profit often manifests itself as liberal progressivism. Critics of this movie are only slamming the message and not even addressing its qualities as a film. The latter is what they are paid to do last I checked. Stations won't air trailers for Unplanned and the MPAA slapped it with an R rating. All done for no reason except to prevent as many people as possible from seeing it. Why is that? What are they afraid of? If they are so chill with a women's right to choose then they should be comfortable defending their stance and addressing questions people may have after seeing it. I honestly think most pro abortion people will avoid this movie because they are afraid of what they might see. The humanizing of those who they dehumanize might make things inconvenient for them.

text: I saw the movie and liked it.  It is VERY tough to see in some places (not explicit but unflinching in portraying what the abortion business is about).  But it helps explain how people on both sides think and why they do what they do.  It is also beautiful and fair depiction of complex people.  But...  I do not like this trailer in that it is just a bunch of chopped up clips that seem to be stereotypically presenting the pro-life side in the most hysterical way possible.  One of the great things about the movie is that it is not about ranting and raving (there is only one hateful pro-life person in the movie, whose technique is rejected by the larger 40 Days for Life group whose goal is to love and support the women getting abortions as well as to form bonds with the workers to help change their minds and hearts.)  I think the trailer will turn off any pro-choice person that is considering going and that is a shame.  The movie has considerable value to educate Christians about the true nature of Planned Parenthood, but it would be even more wonderful to have pro-choice people see it.  With the one exception I mentioned (to acknowledge that they exist), there is no hysteria in the movie, just a lot of patience in the people who for the love of God and human beings are working to turn our nation away from abortion.  The movie tells the truth but does not attack people.   A great script, high production values, good acting, character development and deep insight.  Telling a true story with respect and love for the people--both victims and those who support abortion without really understanding it.

text: When Planned Parenthood's founder Margaret Sanger opened her first birth control clinic in 1916, she was employing harsh rhetoric against abortion. Flyers she distributed to women exhorted them in all capitals: "Do not kill, do not take life, but prevent." Sanger's patients were told "that abortion was the wrong way â€“ no matter how early it was performed it was taking life; that contraception was the better way, the safer way â€“ it took a little time, a little trouble, but it was well worthwhile in the long run, because life had not yet begun." Sanger consistently distanced herself from any calls for legal access to abortion, arguing that legal access to contraceptives would remove the need for abortion. So how did we go from this to now Planned Parenthood being the largest killer of kids in America?

text: A great review from Rotten Tomatoes audience critics: STEVEN F says, Better than we expected. LBH, "Christian" movies have a reputation for not being made to the highest production standards. Wooden acting. Saccharin or unlikely plots. Hysterical or overwrought drama.  So my wife and I were pleasantly surprised to see Unplanned this morning at a matinee, where our emotional and intellectual attraction was fully engaged throughout.  This is a well made movie that is honest about the complexities of abortion, and fair to nearly all parties involved.  Early on the movie demonstrates it is a serious, balanced and factual look at the very difficult issue of abortion when it brings us into the procedure room where the protagonist (actress Ashley Bratcher playing the real-life Abby Johnson) witnesses an actual abortion on the screen of an ultrasound for the first time.  Despite having worked her way up the ladder over 8 years in to the position of Director of her local Planned Parenthood clinic, she had never actually seen the procedure, even though she had chosen to abort her own pregnancies twice before.  Lying on one's back enduring a painful medical procedure with eyes closed apparently is not the same as watching an 8 week old baby on a sonogram monitor being probed with a vacuum tube that the baby struggles to evade only to ultimately be sucked away in a hose full of bloody tissue, an empty black hole on the sonogram screen being all that remains of the terminated pregnancy.  This experience in the operating room, witnessing a baby struggling to live only to be sucked into a bio waste container, changes Abby's life immediately. Call it her Red Pill moment. She flees the OR to a nearby closet where she cries uncontrollably.  The rest of the movie walks us through her slow transformation from a reluctant seeker of abortion services 8 years earlier as a college student, to her ascendancy to the Directorship of the same Planned Parenthood facility where her two abortions were facilitated.  We see the terror and shame experienced by the abortion clients as they exit their cars to a cacophony of screaming. well-meaning, but utterly failed abortion protesters holding angry signs with photos of aborted fetuses. And we see the much more effective, praying Christians softly reaching out to Abortionist and abortion seeking client alike, trying to get to know them, speaking in love, showing everyone the utmost respect.  My wife remarked that Abby was "a slow learner", as it takes a full 8 years for her to wake up to the truth of what an abortion is, despite that she is surrounded by family (husband, mother, father) who gently disagree with her participation in the abortion industry.  And what an industry it is, one billion dollars in revenue, supported culturally, financially and politically by some of the wealthiest and most influential people in the world.  I mentioned that almost everyone is treated fairly in this movie. I think the leadership of Planned Parenthood is consistently portrayed in a bad light, cold heartedly driving their staffs to double the number of abortions in order to raise PP's highest margin product - abortion - the "fries and Coke" of the Women's Health industry. There is very little affection or sympathy shown to the leadership of Planned Parenthood, so I guess one could say their portrayal was unfair. But nowhere was it nonfactual, lest this movie would have never been released. Given the enormous financial, cultural and political resources available to the litigious abortion industry it is not possible that any procedures or facts related to Planned Parenthood would have been allowed in to this movie without iron-clad vetting before hand.  The abortion industry does not want you to see this movie.  They sued Abby Johnson shortly after she quit Planned Parenthood in an attempt to shut her up.  They got this movie's official Twitter account banned on the weekend of its release as its follower count climbed to 7,000.  And I have read that the mainstream media (ABC, CBS, NBC, CNN, NYTimes, etc) universally rejected the advertising monies offered to them by this movies producers.  But the days of MSM blackouts are over.  Remember that Twitter suspended the official Twitter account of this movie @UnPlannedMovie on its opening weekend as its follower count climbed to 7,000?  Well, as of this writing, that count is just shy of 300,000.  I urge every person who is not a 100% political partisan abortion advocate to see this movie. If you've ever wondered if the millions of women who have had abortions have regrets. If you've ever wondered if there are kind and prayerful people who understand the pain of weighing an abortion who want to offer any help they can. If you've ever wondered if the abortion procedure is not as painless and easy as Planned Parenthood says it is. You will benefit from seeing this movie.

text: MY OPINION : While i think having an abortion might be traumatising, scaring and should be generally avoided. There are cases where having an abortion could be the best option. I agree with the fact that terminating a pregnancy even though you can take care of the baby is wrong but everything is not that simple. Giving birth to the child is not enough, you need to take care of them, love them, financially support them till they can support themselves, teach them to be good people, educate them and so many other responsibilities that come with having a baby. What life is a child going to have when the parents themselves are unstable.  I know there are many options once you give birth but it doesn't guarantee quality life for the child, it could actually in turn be much more traumatising for them.  Having a child just because society believes that having an abortion is wrong is not going to help either, this could stem resentment, the mother or parents could start seeing the child as a burden, the child would not get the love and attention they deserve. And these are just some of the reasons, there is also the fact that having a child impacts a woman's life in so many ways.. ways i cant even begin to explain. Having a choice is important not only for the future of the parents but also the child.  I hope to never be in a position where I have to choose whether to abort or keep the baby but thats MY choice that doesn't mean that women who do get abortions or are thinking about it should be looked down upon.  It's a tough decision that should really be thought through because choosing life doesn't always guarantee a smooth ride.

text: I was never what you would call pro choice. But when I was younger I was of the opinion that I could see a case for an abortion only under the most dire of circumstances, as one might infer, such as rape, incest, or if the mother's life was in legitimate jeopardy. Then something occured that made me unsure even for those circumstances. What had happened was I did research into how the procedures are done through each trimester. As we all know you can never unsee something. That includes images your mind and conscience create when you read vividly descriptive text.   I don't know if I need to see this film. I'm not being derisive about it. But every now and then I can still see in my mind how an abortion is done. Doing the research was enough to alter my opinion on the matter. If one who is pro choice can do the same and, with a clear conscience, still hold onto their ardent belief then more power to them. I for one can not label such a procedure as health care.

text: I've always been against abortion.  I was adamantly against it when I was a child, even when my mother hatefully screamed in my face about a woman's right to choose.  I suggested such a woman should choose not to have sex.  She said it was impossible.  I would eventually learn that a lot of women hated me for that, and I was content to remain alone and single rather than get involved in the clusterf**k that was the lives of most of the people I knew.  The attitudes of people on this issue are fanatical.  I mentioned one day that it was my birthday, and someone said that I had just had my birthday just months before.  I said it was my real birthday, the anniversary of my conception.  Everyone went silent and gave me a funny look.  I was a little confused until I realized I had made a very controversial political statement among people who seemed to have strong opinions.  You can't serve two masters, and you have to realize how people who favor abortion will hear your point of view, even if you try to soften the blow, or express your opinion in the most indirect way, like celebrating the anniversary of your conception:  they will hear you calling them murderers, and baby killers.  There really is no other way to put it because that's what it is, and it will eventually have to be treated that way.  I had to listen for the rest of my life to my mother's repeated attempts to justify abortion, and she sort of hated me because I had always taken a hard line against it.  At times it seemed as though I broke her spirit.  I was sorry for that, but I could not back down on such an important issue.  If sexual pleasure is to be considered so important that murdering babies is an acceptable trade off, why shouldn't any pleasure be an acceptable excuse for murdering anyone?  If the inconvenience of an unwanted baby is an acceptable reason for killing, why shouldn't any inconvenience be an acceptable reason for killing anyone?  It's hard to live in a world so full of murderers when they hate you for being opposed to murder.  I hate that I have become so accustomed to living in a world where most people hate me, where they must hate me, or they will hate themselves. (The G:  i will praise thee for i am fearfully and wonderfully made marvellous are thy works and that my soul knoweth right well)

text: I just want to say, I'm a mom of 4 kids who has never had an abortion. I have been to planned parenthood for regular exams when I didn't have insurance, and I also went there later for pregnancy verification, which I needed for insurance to cover prenatal care. When I got my pregnancy verification, the staff at PP were very supportive, offered materials about local groups that helped with baby supplies, and were in general very congratulatory and happy for me. There was not even a remote suggestion that I should get an abortion. My adult daughter also used planned parenthood for her exams and for birth control when she didn't have insurance as well. Luckily we now both have insurance and have regular doctors, but the majority of what PP does is NOT abortion. And the majority of people who work there are not monsters devaluing human life and acting like corporate witches.    Want to end abortion? Here's how you do it. Create a society without extreme poverty. Demand decent low-cost housing and the demolition of all substandard public housing projects. Guarantee the same level of excellent public education to all citizens, regardless of income (Finland does this, and has one of the best education systems on the planet, if not the best). Provide universal health care and a universal basic income to all citizens. Provide early and extensive sexual education and free birth control to all citizens. Provide low-cost or free public  higher education or trade programs. In essence, turn this society into a place where no person has an excuse to get mindlessly pregnant and then no choice but to abort. You can't keep turning the country into a shithole where 9 guys own everything and poor kids are going to schools with mold infestations and no books and your government claims to care about "life" while selling white phosphorus to Saudi Arabia and then expect people to care about unborn fetuses. We don't even appear to care about the living children who exist in this country - why would anyone care about ones that haven't even been born yet? Until you're willing to do what needs to be done, you have absolutely zero moral high ground on this, the end.

text: Speaking from personal experience, what we should be doing is approaching this problem before conception. What else are you going to do? You can't lock girls and women up and force them to carry and deliver their babies. We have to change people's mindset from the inside out so that they would never consider an abortion whether it's legal or not. Religionists have to come off the moral high ground, get into the trenches, and get real. Birth control should be readily available free of charge to any sexually active person, female or male, and regardless of a particular employer's religious beliefs!! Don't take Sex Ed out of schools when you know very well that many parents are abdicating their responsibility in this regard. Society must quit shaming women as "welfare queens" and accept that they chose life for their babies, for whatever reason and even if our taxes have to help support those children! Churches, schools, leaders of youth groups: You know the signs. Help at risk children and families BEFORE they get into circumstances that lead to teen pregnancy. No one was there for me despite attending Catholic school for 12 years. Of course, parishioners brought food and clothing to our home occasionally, but there was no real social intervention. I lived in a broken home with 10 brothers and sisters, an absent father, an overwhelmed mother who had to go back to work to support us (I can't even imagine), no adult supervision at home, and no guidance at church or school. I had my baby when I was a junior and gave her up adoption. I wanted to keep her, but that just wasn't done 50 years ago.  People forget that adoption hurts, too. I hope my daughter is having a good and happy life. I've lived with guilt all of mine. If you've read this far, thank you.

text: Unplanned continues its strong showing at the box office as it heads into its second weekend of release. Box office receipts for Friday April 5, 2019, the 8th day of its release, place Unplanned at #8 nationwide. Now showing on an expanded 1,516 theater screens across America, Unplanned pulled in another $1,040,000 at the box office with a strong per theater average of $656, bringing the total in box office receipts to $10,307,510 which far surpasses the negative expectations for the pro-life movie that the abortion lobby and its media partners predicted during their all out pre-release war to block Unplanned from being shown or advertised in most major media outlets. Comparing Unplanned's stellar showing at the box office thus far with the recently released pro-abortion propaganda documentary RBG which attempted to sell the life and career of rabidly pro-abortion Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg as a champion of liberty and women's rights, it is abundantly clear that Americans' pocketbooks are choosing a Pro-Life message over that of abortion industry dogma. While RBG received Oscar nominations and idolatrous worship across the same secular media platforms that have vigorously tried to blacklist and boycott Unplanned, Americans are using their feet and their dollars to tell the media and the movie industry that the days of selling to America an unchallenged pro-abortion message without consequences are over. After 8 days of box office ticket sales, RBG had only accumulated a total of $702,044 compared to Unplanned's 8 day total of $10,040,000. It took RBG 45 days to earn $10 Million in box office receipts and that was only done with the assistance of every major liberal newspaper, magazine and tv news channel promoting it as some sort of "glorious and heroic" masterpiece. While the pro-abortion lobby which controls the Academy Awards made sure RBG received two Oscar nominations for Best Documentary and Best Original Song, Americans can expect Unplanned to be treated by the Academy Awards with the same contempt that it showed towards Mel Gibson's masterpiece The Passion of The Christ. However, at the end of the day it is neither money nor awards which matter. What truly matters is how many lives are saved from the for-profit abortion mills of Planned Parenthood. Like Nazi Germany's concentration camps during World War II, America has already seen an entire generation of human babies of all races and genders wiped from the face of the earth in the abortion mills of Planned Parenthood. text: I just saw this movie today after my mom asked me to go with her. I didn't know what to expect and honestly wasn't really keen on seeing it. I went into it thinking it was going to be a really controversial, extremely conservative, boring documentary, but it definitely wasn't. No matter where you stand on the subject of abortion, you SHOULD SEE THIS MOVIE. Just go into it with an open mind, and maybe you'll come out knowing something you didn't going in. If you are strictly pro-choice are you going to walk out of the theater completely changed? Maybe not. But what's so great about this movie is that it's raw and real. It's not sugarcoated. It is definitely hard to watch at times, just FYI, but that's what we need. It shows what goes on inside a Planned Parenthood and how the decision to get an abortion or even to become pregnant in the first place affects people's lives, and that's the kind of awareness we need. Of course no media outlets are promoting this movie and honestly that's just sad. My point is is that no matter what side of the aisle you're on, if you go see this movie I guarantee you won't regret it. I think you'll come out with more of an open mind on the topic, that's all. I'm so glad I saw it. The acting by the lead girl was amazing btw, hope to see more of her in the future. Also fyi- bring a box of tissues!

text: My husband is a paralegal and has read the Roe v Wade decision. He describes it as "a decision in search of a case". She was their sock puppet. Under any other circumstances she might be facing prison time for something like that. In 1995 she became a Christian and then made it her goal to see Roe v Wade overturned in her lifetime. Sadly it didn't happen; she passed away a few years ago.  Don't listen to the scare stories of what will happen if Roe v Wade gets overturned. You're going to hear about poor, helpless women having to submit to back alley abortions with coat hangers and judgmental Christians who will make sure women know their place. What will REALLY happen is that the authority whether or not to have abortions will go back to the individual states, which is how it was before 1973. If this were to happen, Banned Parenthood would lose their federal funding. As usual, follow the money. text: 3 most popular pro-choice arguments debunked  1. Birth poses a threat to her body, so it's self defence to kill it  Don't you think that birth poses a threat to the child's health as well? Women's pelvic bones can seriously damage the fetus. Brachial plexus injury occurs in 1-3 children per 1000 births. Every year there are 10 000 born children diagnosed with cerebral palsy every year (https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birth_injury). As you can see on Wikipedia, birth can cause them bone fractures, brain damage, bruises or meconium aspiration syndrome which can lead to pneumonia and pneumothorax. In fact, birth poses greater danger to children than to mothers. No danger for the fetus would occur if the baby didn't need to travel through cervix and vagina out of the woman's body. Do you think we should cut her in half so the child has a 100% of being born uninjured? Just as I don't approve cutting the mother in two, so the child can get out easier and with no risk of head damage, I do not approve killing the fetus, crushing its skull and tearing it apart limb by limb to lower the maternal mortality rate, which is already very low (12 deaths per 100 000 women in developed countries (https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/maternal-mortality)).    2. No one is allowed to use my body against my will  That's true, but if you don't want anyone in your house, you and your partner shouldn't lead them in the first place. If you don't want them, wait at least 9 months for them to come out and don't shoot them. Do you think that if someone else in case of rape and basically you and your partner in case of consentual sex stuck one's head in your window and can't pull it out, should you be allowed to legally chop off their head in order to have a view out of a window again?  We have to think about the definition of responsibility. Responsibility is ability to willingly make an action to prevent or make something to happen. Is fetus a burglar who voluntarily and consciously got into you against your will? Is fetus responsible for being inside the mother? Unlike its mother who really is responsible in more than 99% (excluding case of rape), it is not. Only two people responsible for conception of a child are the parents. Everyone who's allowed to have sex knows of the risks of getting pregnant and catching an STD. Would you blame others for catching an STD?   I am sorry that someone you and your partner threw off a cliff is holding your hand, but you can't let them fall (actually in reality you don't just let them fall but you actually kill them). Wait 9 months unil they climb up. You both deserve equal protection and no one can kill any of you.    3. It's not human  What determines when it's human? Â  Heartbeat? What about the people living with an artificial heart and a pacemaker? Â Brain function? Fetuses have a slightly different brain function because they dont use all of their senses yet and dont move much. Its like a sleeping person. And newborns have lesser brain function than us as well.  If you say that before 6 weeks it's not human because it has not fully developed arms is a bad argument because there are people without arms. Without legs, even without hearts who live with a artificial hearths. Every human is a living integrated cluster of cells filled with human DNA. Nothing more.  Shouldn't we than kill children because they have no permanent teeth, so they are not fully human?  If you think that fetuses aren't fully human, because their brains aren't fully formed, human brains develop until 20 or 30 years after birth (https://mentalhealthdaily.com/2015/02/18/at-what-age-is-the-brain-fully-developed/).  Every single one species on this planet came into being as a single cell who in most cases didn't resemble the final mature individual. Development of the human organism both prenatal and postatal is on Wikipedia (https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Development_of_the_human_body). You can clearly see that every scientific article regards embryos and fetuses as humans who just aren't fully mature yet - just like children.

Some states don't have any laws about telling your parents or getting their permission. But some states say you have to get permission from a parent or older family member to have an abortion. Other states donâ€™t make you get permission, but your parents will have to know that youâ€™re getting an abortion.   You may be able to get a judge's permission to have an abortion without telling your parents. This is called "judicial bypass".  The exact rules are different in different places. Find information on parental involvement in your state below.  And know that youâ€™re not alone. If youâ€™re pregnant and want to have an abortion, call your nearest Planned Parenthood health center as soon as possible. They can help explain the laws in your state, let you know what your options are, and give you tips on talking with your parents.  It's important to take action right away. text: My first thought when I heard about this movie was well, who better to give a well-rounded look at abortion than someone who has confidently walked both sides of the issue? I think if anyone was confident about a huge part of their life and job, and then was in shock to that degree over facts they learned, then they would probably want to tell someone.  No matter what view you have on abortion, you should admire this woman for her courage for speaking her truth. text: Back in 2008, my baby sister (she's 14 y.o. younger than myself) called me, really, really upset... She was 18, still in school, 6 months before finals - and pregnant. She needed advice, and called me as well to seek mine.   What I told her, with love but also bluntly - she will have to make the decision about keeping the baby all by herself. No religion, no mother, no siblings are allowed to make it. It's her body, her choice. But she can be sure about one thing: I will always be on her side, regardless of her choice; I will love her and I will support her decision, completely.   After talking to he boyfriend, they both decided to keep the baby. We have a gorgeous smart girl now in our family, and we all love her, and protect her... So everything ended up like a Hallmark movie.   In their case, it was a moment when they just ignored the precautions, and ... just happened. Fortunately, the end was a happy one, but we all know - that isn't always the case. There are raped minors, there are dangerous situations for both of them, illnesses or malformations that can ruin much more than just one life. We need to expand sexual education programs, we need to educate people to understand the risks. We need to fight sexism and extreme religious intolerance that only lead to abuse, forced marriages, lack of education... We need access to health programs, and also maybe to reform the adoption procedures, to help mothers that cannot afford a child to carry to term then help a family to adopt and give a warm shelter to that baby...    Instead of blaming and pointing fingers, quoting the holly books and despising, we need to re-learn to love, understand, protect, listen.

text: At least for me, when it comes to either side on this debate, the pro-life (or as I like to say, "pro-birth") or the pro-choice group, the difficult thing for me is that the main arguments for both sides end up being complete bull#$%^: Pro-Life "Abortion is murder" argument: Considering that the definition of murder is "the unlawful killing of a human being with malice aforethought," even if you believe it is unlawful in all circumstances, that it involves the "killing of a human being" (which I do, BTW), there is absolutely NO way that you can prove that all abortions are done from "malice aforethought," especially in the case of the woman who are undergoing abortions, and thus this argument falls apart. Pro-Choice "My body, my rules" argument: Considering that when we're talking about another living human within the mother's womb (just as I believe it isn't hard to say that a kitten with a cat's womb or a puppy within a dog's womb is still a cat or dog), when you make a choice here, it isn't JUST about "your body": its about the BABY's body too, and thus this argument falls apart. Personally, I'm one of those folks who believe that abortion should be "rare but legal" (e.g. in cases of rape and incest or the mother's life is at risk), but in the end, I just want to say that if anyone wishes to really make any good progress on issues like these, it is critical to 1) not straw-man the other side 2) give reasonable arguments which aren't full of bull@#$% and 3) to simply BE THERE for these poor women going through these climactic times in their lives. Anyway, those are my 2 cents on the issue, and I'll see what I think of the movie when I hopefully see it in the following week.

text: For anyone who's asking, "How could anybody be pro-choice?" I'm pro-choice and here's why. I personally don't believe that life begins at conception, I believe that life begins with brain activity. But I know that that is a very personal belief that I can't convince anyone to change. But something that others need to realize is that plenty of pro-choicers don't like abortion. A lot of us think it's sad. BUT what we realize is that banning abortion has never actually reduced the number of abortions, it just stops women from having safe, clean places to have the procedure. For example, when Romania banned abortion in 1966, the motherhood mortality rate doubled (source: https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/05/16/what-actually-happens-when-a-country-bans-abortion-romania-alabama/ ). Bans also disproportionately affect poor women, while rich women are always able to bribe someone to have the procedure done safely. If you actually want to reduce abortion, fight for better access to sex ed and birth control. But history has shown that bans DON'T WORK and instead only put women's lives at risk. And if you think that women who want abortions should deserve to die, then there's nothing I can say to you.
